  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 천승(千乘) : '
    value: 승은 수레를 셈하는 단위. 주대(周代)에 전쟁이 있으면 천자는 만승(萬乘), 제후는 천승을 내게 하였는데, 바꾸어서 제후를 천승이라 하였다.
english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Grateful Rain
  author: Byeon Gyeliang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the hamlet of Yongsan's Standing Stone, the world speaks of pleasures found in lakes and mountains. Scarcely two leagues from the capital, the Lord of Filial Peace once established his country retreat. Behind it rose a hill, rounded and sinuous as a coiled dragon, and upon it was built a pavilion—a place of rest.

    The Lord said to me: "The Sovereign, in early morning procession, went forth to inspect the fields. He graced this pavilion with his presence, bestowing upon me wine and provisions and fine horses. It was the season of planting, yet the rains had not sufficed. As the feast progressed, rain began to fall—heavy and continuous through the day. The Sovereign named the pavilion 'Grateful for Rain,' and my heart overflows with gratitude. I wish to honor the imperial gift. I have commissioned Vice-Minister Shin Saek to inscribe the three characters 'Pavilion of Grateful Rain' upon its wall. Write an account to commemorate this."

    One day I ascended the pavilion with the Lord. Its structure was neither extravagant nor crude. Mount Hwa bows behind it; the Han River surges before its breast. To the southwest, distant peaks fade into misty blue, appearing and vanishing like dreams beyond clouds and waters. Below, fish and shrimp could be counted one by one. Sails and shore-birds passed beneath like objects upon a table. A thousand pine trees stood verdant and dense, their shadows dancing upon the wine cups. High pipes sang shrilly; a clear wind swept in—and I seemed to sprout wings and ascend to heaven's vault, to float upon the wind toward the islands of immortals. My eyes startled, my hair stood on end, and long did I remain in silent wonder before departing.

    I have pondered this: Man and Heaven-and-Earth are originally one body. Thus it is said: "When equilibrium and harmony are achieved, Heaven takes its place and all things flourish." Even in the subtlest thought and gentlest word, the resonance between Heaven and humanity rings clear and irrefutable. Yet virtue has its degrees, and position its ranks. The breadth and swiftness of this resonance vary accordingly. Only an emperor or sage can fully comprehend this mystery.

    I humbly reflect: Our Sovereign possesses talents granted by Heaven itself, the rarest in ages. He cultivates the learning of the sages to achieve perfect equilibrium and harmony, to bring all things to their fullest flourishing. This is boundless and beyond naming. Today's rain is but one manifestation of this.

    Our Sovereign's love for the people runs deep within his heart. When he journeyed to the fields to inspect the harvest, a compassionate yearning for rain arose unbidden—and Heaven responded as swift as turning a clock. The Sovereign's profound benevolence flows like that rain, filling the spaces between Heaven-and-Earth, transforming sorrow to joy and healing the afflicted. From the smallest blade of grass to the mightiest tree, all attain their nature's fulfillment. The pavilion bears the name 'Grateful for Rain' so that we might never forget Heaven's gift.

    Alas! Since the Qin and Han, many have lost their equilibrium with Heaven. People and creatures withered; the cosmos grew barren. How sorrowful! Yet we are born into this age, blessed with imperial grace. Even the beasts and plants share in this fortune—how can we not rejoice? And for those of us clothed in purple robes, serving in the halls of power, receiving the Sovereign's regard—this is a meeting with fortune that comes once in a thousand years.

    The Lord, being of royal kinship, ranks high in honor and wealth beyond compare, yet receives the Sovereign's deep affection. Our Sovereign, seated in supreme authority, shared this pavilion with the Lord, conversing as intimately as in former days of seclusion. Such glory transcends the power of brush and ink to describe. This springs from the Sovereign's natural virtue of affection, expressed with utmost sincerity—so much so that he seems to forget his station as ruler of all people. How sublime!

    The Lord himself is humble and kind, bearing his wealth and rank without arrogance. He is the mirror of the royal house, its shield and support. Small wonder he receives such deep affection from the Sovereign.

    How strange that this beautiful realm, present since the world's division, lay hidden through endless ages, only to reveal itself now! Perhaps because the Lord's heart, though dwelling amid worldly splendor, perpetually wanders in mountain valleys and river gorges. Thus Heaven and Earth bestow this place upon him as consolation.

    The beauty of these mountains and waters, the transformations of dawn and dusk, of the four seasons—though my body is afflicted, perhaps in time I shall again accompany the Lord through this pavilion and compose verses upon its charm. For now, I offer these humble words, though they fail to illuminate the Sovereign's purpose in naming the pavilion. Like measuring the sea with a gourd or painting heaven with a brush, my effort falls far short. Yet to inscribe my name beside this memorial is itself a great honor. As fireflies endure through the radiance of sun and moon, and humble plants persist through reliance on heaven and earth, so do I rejoice at this unexpected fortune.

    Therefore I have written gladly, and composed this song:

    Soaring stands the new pavilion,
    Like a phoenix in flight—
    Who was its maker?
    The virtuous Lord, none other.

    The Sovereign journeyed westward,
    Not for sport, not for the hunt,
    But the people sowed their seeds
    While drought parched the fields.

    The Sovereign sat in the pavilion,
    When timely rain fell copious,
    And feasted with the Lord—
    Drums thundered deep and long.

    He bestowed upon it a name,
    Glory beyond all precedent,
    And the Lord bowed low,
    Grateful as Heaven itself.

    May the Sovereign reign ten thousand years!
    We sought out the men of letters
    To make this endure in memory—
    I bow and take up my brush.

    Look upon Mount Hwa's peaks:
    Those stones deserve inscription,
    That these verses of praise
    May shine through endless ages.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Pavilion of Grateful Rain' commemorates a visit by the Sovereign to inspect agricultural fields during a drought, after which timely rain fell—understood as heaven's response to the ruler's compassionate concern.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Lord' (君侯) refers to Prince Hyolyeong, who commissioned this record from the author.
  - key: ''
    value: Mount Hwa refers to the Hwaak Mountains near present-day Seoul.
  - key: ''
    value: References to 'the islands of immortals' and 'floating on the wind' draw upon classical Daoist imagery of transcendence and mystical union with nature.
  - key: ''
    value: The concept of 'equilibrium and harmony' (中和) is drawn from Neo-Confucian philosophy, particularly the *Doctrine of the Mean*, suggesting the ruler's virtue naturally harmonizes with cosmic forces.
